            @* What is Design Thinking? *@
            <div>
                <h3>
                    What is Design Thinking?
                </h3>
                <p>
                    Design thinking is a problem-solving approach that has gained popularity in recent years. It is a
                    human-centric approach to innovation that involves understanding the needs of the user and
                    developing
                    solutions that meet those needs. In this article, we will explore the basics of design thinking and
                    its
                    applications.
                </p>
                <p> Design thinking methodology involves cross-functional
                    teams working together to develop solutions that meet the user’s needs. Meaning Design thinking is
                    not a
                    single method or tool, but a mindset and a process that involves five stages: empathize, define,
                    ideate,
                    prototype, and test:
                <ul class="h5">
                    <li>
                        <b>
                            Empathize:
                        </b>
                        In this stage, the team seeks to understand the user’s needs and challenges. This involves
                        conducting research, observing users, and gathering data.
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <b>
                            Define:
                        </b>
                        In this stage, the team defines the problem based on the insights gathered in the empathize
                        stage.
                        The team creates a problem statement that guides the ideation process
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <b>
                            Ideate:
                        </b>
                        In this stage, the team generates ideas for solutions to the problem. The team uses
                        brainstorming
                        techniques to generate a wide range of ideas.

                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <b>
                            Prototype:
                        </b>
                        In this stage, the team creates a prototype of the solution. The prototype can be a physical
                        model
                        or a digital representation of the solution.
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <b>
                            Test:
                        </b>
                        In this stage, the team tests the prototype with users to gather feedback. The feedback is used
                        to
                        refine the solution and make improvements.
                    </li>
                </ul>
                </p>
            </div>
